## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA was removed from macOS**. `DSA.Create()` now throws at runtime on macOS — it still works on Windows and Linux.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy signatures** (not create new ones), you have two options:

1. **Platform guard** — skip DSA verification on macOS and run it only on Windows/Linux:
   ```csharp
   if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
   {
       using var dsa = DSA.Create();
       // verify signature...
   }
   ```

2. **Migrate to a modern algorithm** (recommended long-term) — re-sign your data with **ECDSA** or **RSA**, then verify with the new algorithm on all platforms:
   ```csharp
   using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
   bool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
   ```

If you can't re-sign the legacy data, option 1 (the platform guard) keeps macOS builds running while you verify on the platforms that still support DSA. You could also use a third-party crypto library (e.g., Bouncy Castle) to verify DSA signatures portably on all platforms including macOS.
